{# ══ Review ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call reviewSection() %}
<p>Expand each concept to check your understanding before moving on.</p>

<div class="accordion mt-3" id="u01-review">
  {% call accordion("rev-u01-a", "Proposition — what is it and how do you recognise one?") %}
  <p>A proposition is a declarative statement that has a truth value — it is either true or false (or indeterminate). Questions, commands, and exclamations are not propositions. A proposition can be false and still be a proposition: the key criterion is that it <em>could</em> be true or false.</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u01-b", "Truth values — what are the three possibilities?") %}
  <p><strong>True (T)</strong>: the proposition corresponds to the facts. <strong>False (F)</strong>: it does not. <strong>Indeterminate</strong>: we cannot assign a definite truth value — due to vagueness, paradox, or incomplete evidence. Classical (two-valued) logic uses only T and F; some logics add a third value.</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u01-c", "Three theories of truth — what are they?") %}
  <p><strong>Correspondence</strong>: a proposition is true if it corresponds to facts about the world. <strong>Coherence</strong>: a proposition is true if it coheres with a system of accepted beliefs. <strong>Pragmatic</strong>: a proposition is true if acting on it produces successful outcomes. Formal logic predominantly uses the correspondence view.</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u01-d", "Premise, conclusion, reasoning, argument — how do they relate?") %}
  <p>An <strong>argument</strong> consists of one or more <strong>premises</strong> (the evidence offered) and a <strong>conclusion</strong> (the claim being supported). <strong>Reasoning</strong> is the process by which we move from premises to conclusion. Not every passage with opinions is an argument — there must be an attempt to provide reasons for a conclusion.</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u01-e", "P and Q notation — what does it mean?") %}
  <p>P and Q are propositional variables — letters that stand for any proposition. Writing <em>If P, then Q</em> expresses a conditional relationship between two propositions without specifying their content. This notation lets us analyse the <em>structure</em> of an argument separately from its subject matter.</p>
  {% endcall %}
</div>

